"# Chapter 14: Transcription & Transposition

You hear a melody. You want to capture it, shift it, play it back in a different key, or hand it to another instrument. Until now we've built sound from instructions—frequencies, envelopes, filters. This chapter reverses the flow: we *listen* to sound and extract its structure. Transcription reads audio into a score of pitches and timing. Transposition shifts that score by an interval or ratio, preserving shape while changing register or key. Together they let the runtime hear a phrase, write it down, and re-voice it.

We'll drill pitch detection, note-onset timing, interval arithmetic, and key-shift by ratio. The crescendo: capture a melody, transcribe it to pitches, transpose it up a fifth, and play it back on a different instrument.

[VISUAL: Waveform → spectrum analysis → detected pitches on a staff → transposed staff → new waveform]

---

## What Transcription Means

Transcription converts audio into discrete events: pitches, start times, durations. It's the inverse of synthesis. Where `(tone 440 0.5)` *makes* an A4 for half a second, transcription *hears* that A4 and writes `(440 0.5)` into a data structure.

The engine performs pitch detection by analyzing the spectrum over time (Chapter 13's FFT, windowed and tracked). It returns a list of `(pitch time duration)` tuples.

<!-- BUILD: transcribe returns list of (pitch-hz start-sec dur-sec) tuples from audio buffer -->

```scheme
;; Transcribe a single pure tone
(let ((recording (tone 440 1.0)))
  (transcribe recording))
;; => ((440 0.0 1.0))
```
*[needs: transcribe]*

The result: one event at 440 Hz, starting at time zero, lasting one second.

---

## Transcribing a Short Phrase

A phrase of several notes yields several tuples.

```scheme
;; Record three tones in sequence
(let ((phrase (list (tone 262 0.3)   ; C4
                    (tone 330 0.3)   ; E4
                    (tone 392 0.3)))) ; G4
  (transcribe phrase))
;; => ((262 0.0 0.3) (330 0.3 0.3) (392 0.6 0.3))
```
*[needs: transcribe, audio concatenation]*

Each tuple captures the pitch, its start time relative to the phrase, and its duration.

---

## Transposition by Ratio

Transposition multiplies each pitch by a ratio. To shift up one octave, multiply by 2. To shift up a perfect fifth (3:2), multiply by 1.5.

```scheme
;; Transpose a single pitch up one octave
(let ((original 440))
  (* original 2))
;; => 880
```

The function `(transpose notes interval)` applies this across a list of notes. An interval can be a ratio (1.5 for a fifth) or a named interval.

<!-- BUILD: transpose takes list of (pitch start dur) and interval, returns scaled list -->

```scheme
;; Transpose a melody up a perfect fifth
(let ((melody '((262 0.0 0.3) (330 0.3 0.3) (392 0.6 0.3))))
  (transpose melody 1.5))
;; => ((393 0.0 0.3) (495 0.3 0.3) (588 0.6 0.3))
```
*[needs: transpose]*

C4 (262 Hz) becomes 393 Hz (roughly G4), E4 becomes B4, G4 becomes D5. The shape is preserved, the register raised by a fifth.

---

## Transposition by Semitones

Equal temperament divides the octave into twelve semitones, each a ratio of 2^(1/12) ≈ 1.05946. To transpose up *n* semitones, multiply by 2^(n/12).

```scheme
;; Transpose a pitch up 7 semitones (a perfect fifth in 12-TET)
(let ((original 440)
      (semitones 7))
  (* original (expt 2 (/ semitones 12))))
;; => ~659.25 Hz (E5)
```

We can wrap this in a helper:

```scheme
(define (semitone-shift pitch n)
  (* pitch (expt 2 (/ n 12))))

(semitone-shift 440 12)  ; up one octave
;; => 880.0
```

---

## Transposing a Captured Melody

Combine transcription with transposition: record audio, extract pitches, shift them, and play back.

```scheme
;; Capture, transcribe, transpose, play
(define (capture-transpose-play shift-ratio)
  (let* ((original (list (tone 262 0.25)
                         (tone 294 0.25)
                         (tone 330 0.25)
                         (tone 349 0.25)))
         (notes (transcribe original))
         (shifted (transpose notes shift-ratio)))
    (map (lambda (n)
           (tone (car n) (caddr n)))
         shifted)))

(capture-transpose-play 1.5)  ; up a fifth
```
*[needs: transcribe, transpose, audio sequencing]*

The original C-D-E-F becomes G-A-B-C at the fifth.

---

## Preserving Timing

Transposition affects pitch, not time. The start and duration fields remain unchanged.

```scheme
;; Transpose without altering timing
(let ((melody '((440 0.0 0.5) (494 0.5 0.5) (523 1.0 0.5))))
  (transpose melody 2.0))  ; up one octave
;; => ((880 0.0 0.5) (988 0.5 0.5) (1046 1.0 0.5))
```
*[needs: transpose]*

The rhythm is identical; only the pitches doubled.

---

## Down-Transposition

Ratios less than 1 transpose downward.

```scheme
;; Transpose down one octave
(let ((melody '((880 0.0 0.3) (988 0.3 0.3) (1046 0.6 0.3))))
  (transpose melody 0.5))
;; => ((440 0.0 0.3) (494 0.3 0.3) (523 0.6 0.3))
```
*[needs: transpose]*

A5-B5-C6 becomes A4-B4-C5.

---

## Negative Semitone Shift

Use a negative semitone count to transpose down.

```scheme
(define (semitone-shift pitch n)
  (* pitch (expt 2 (/ n 12))))

(semitone-shift 440 -12)  ; down one octave
;; => 220.0
```

---

## Transposing by Named Intervals

We can define interval names as ratios and apply them.

```scheme
(define intervals
  '((unison . 1.0)
    (minor-second . 1.0595)
    (major-second . 1.1225)
    (minor-third . 1.1892)
    (major-third . 1.2599)
    (perfect-fourth . 1.3348)
    (tritone . 1.4142)
    (perfect-fifth . 1.4983)
    (minor-sixth . 1.5874)
    (major-sixth . 1.6818)
    (minor-seventh . 1.7818)
    (major-seventh . 1.8877)
    (octave . 2.0)))

(define (interval-ratio name)
  (cdr (assoc name intervals)))

(* 440 (interval-ratio 'perfect-fifth))
;; => ~659.252 Hz
```

---

## Transposing a Melody by Named Interval

```scheme
(define intervals
  '((perfect-fifth . 1.4983)
    (major-third . 1.2599)
    (octave . 2.0)))

(define (interval-ratio name)
  (cdr (assoc name intervals)))

(let ((melody '((262 0.0 0.3) (330 0.3 0.3) (392 0.6 0.3)))
      (shift (interval-ratio 'major-third)))
  (transpose melody shift))
;; => C-E-G shifted up a major third
```
*[needs: transpose]*

---

## Handling Polyphony

If transcription detects overlapping pitches (a chord), each note gets its own tuple. Transposition applies independently to each voice.

```scheme
;; Transcribe a two-note harmony
(let ((chord (list (tone 262 0.5) (tone 330 0.5))))
  (transcribe chord))
;; => ((262 0.0 0.5) (330 0.0 0.5))
```
*[needs: transcribe, simultaneous audio]*

Both notes start at time zero. Transposing the result shifts both pitches by the same ratio, preserving the interval between them.

---

## Transposing Chords

```scheme
;; Transpose a C major triad up a perfect fourth
(let ((triad '((262 0.0 1.0) (330 0.0 1.0) (392 0.0 1.0)))
      (fourth 1.3348))
  (transpose triad fourth))
;; => F major triad
```
*[needs: transpose]*

The 4:5:6 ratio (major triad) is preserved; the root moves from C to F.

---

## Key Signature and Scale Degree

Transposition by ratio is *chromatic*—it shifts by exact frequency multiplication. To transpose *diatonically* (within a scale), we'd map scale degrees rather than raw pitches. That requires a scale definition and degree lookup, which we'll visit in the Music book. Here we focus on chromatic (ratio-based) transposition.

---

## Detecting Vibrato

If the input has vibrato (periodic pitch modulation), transcription may yield multiple close pitches or a single pitch with a vibrato annotation, depending on the engine's resolution. For now, we treat the detected pitch as the mean.

<!-- BUILD: vibrato detection / pitch smoothing in transcription -->

```scheme
;; Transcribe a tone with gentle vibrato (conceptual)
;; Engine returns mean pitch if vibrato variance is small
(let ((vibrato-tone (tone 440 1.0)))  ; imagine modulated pitch
  (transcribe vibrato-tone))
;; => ((440 0.0 1.0))  ; mean pitch
```
*[needs: transcribe]*

---

## Transcribing Rhythm

Transcription captures onset time and duration. If two notes have identical pitch but different start times, they appear as separate events.

```scheme
;; Two A4 notes with a gap
(let ((phrase (list (tone 440 0.3)
                    ; 0.2 sec silence
                    (tone 440 0.3))))
  (transcribe phrase))
;; => ((440 0.0 0.3) (440 0.5 0.3))
```
*[needs: transcribe, audio sequencing with silence]*

The rhythm is encoded in the start-time deltas.

---

## Transposing Percussion (Frequency-Shift)

Transposing a drum hit by ratio shifts its spectral content. A snare at fundamental ~200 Hz transposed by 1.5 yields a higher, thinner snare.

```scheme
;; Transpose a noise-based snare up a fifth (conceptual)
(let ((snare-note '((200 0.0 0.15))))  ; fundamental detected
  (transpose snare-note 1.5))
;; => ((300 0.0 0.15))
```
*[needs: transpose, noise-based transcription]*

The result is spectrally shifted, not pitch-shifted in the melodic sense, but the math is identical.

---

## Round-Trip: Tone → Transcription → Transposition → Playback

```scheme
;; Generate, transcribe, transpose, regenerate
(define (round-trip freq dur shift)
  (let* ((original (tone freq dur))
         (notes (transcribe original))
         (shifted (transpose notes shift))
         (new-freq (car (car shifted)))
         (new-dur (caddr (car shifted))))
    (tone new-freq new-dur)))

(round-trip 440 0.5 2.0)  ; A4 → A5
```
*[needs: transcribe, transpose]*

The output is a tone one octave higher.

---

## Batch Transposition

Apply several transpositions to the same melody to hear it in multiple keys.

```scheme
;; Transpose a melody by several intervals
(define (multi-transpose melody intervals)
  (map (lambda (i) (transpose melody i)) intervals))

(let ((mel '((262 0.0 0.3) (330 0.3 0.3) (392 0.6 0.3))))
  (multi-transpose mel '(1.0 1.2599 1.4983)))
;; => original, up maj3, up p5
```
*[needs: transpose]*

Returns a list of transposed melodies.

---

## Transposing by Octave and Semitone

Combine octave shift (multiply by 2^k) with semitone shift (multiply by 2^(n/12)).

```scheme
(define (transpose-oct-semi pitch octaves semitones)
  (* pitch (expt 2 octaves) (expt 2 (/ semitones 12))))

(transpose-oct-semi 440 1 7)  ; up 1 oct + 7 semi = E6
;; => 1318.5 Hz
```

---

## Inverting an Interval

Inversion flips an interval: a fifth (3:2) inverted is a fourth (4:3). For transcription, we invert by dividing instead of multiplying.

```scheme
;; Transpose down by the inversion of a fifth (i.e., down a fourth)
(let ((melody '((440 0.0 0.3)))
      (fifth-inverse (/ 1 1.4983)))
  (transpose melody fifth-inverse))
;; => ((293.7 0.0 0.3))  ; ~D4
```
*[needs: transpose]*

A4 down a fourth yields D4.

---

## Cents and Microtonal Transposition

A cent is 1/100 of a semitone, ratio 2^(1/1200). Transpose by *n* cents:

```scheme
(define (cents-shift pitch cents)
  (* pitch (expt 2 (/ cents 1200))))

(cents-shift 440 50)  ; up 50 cents (quarter-tone)
;; => ~452.9 Hz
```

---

## Transposing with Microtonal Precision

```scheme
;; Transpose a melody up 33 cents (1/3 semitone)
(let ((melody '((440 0.0 0.5)))
      (shift (expt 2 (/ 33 1200))))
  (transpose melody shift))
;; => ((451.05 0.0 0.5))
```
*[needs: transpose]*

Useful for tuning systems outside 12-TET.

---

## Transposing to Match a Reference Pitch

Given a reference pitch, compute the ratio from the original root and transpose the whole melody.

```scheme
(define (transpose-to-match melody old-root new-root)
  (let ((ratio (/ new-root old-root)))
    (transpose melody ratio)))

(let ((mel '((262 0.0 0.3) (330 0.3 0.3) (392 0.6 0.3))))
  (transpose-to-match mel 262 294))  ; C to D
;; => melody transposed up a major second
```
*[needs: transpose]*

---

## Combining Transcription and Envelope Detection

Transcription yields pitch and timing. If the engine also detects amplitude envelope, we can capture dynamics.

<!-- BUILD: transcribe returns amplitude envelope or peak amplitude per note -->

```scheme
;; Transcribe with dynamics (conceptual)
(let ((recording (tone 440 0.5)))
  (transcribe recording))
;; => ((440 0.0 0.5 :amplitude 0.8))
```
*[needs: transcribe with dynamics]*

Transposition preserves amplitude.

---

## Transposing and Re-voicing

After transposition, play the new pitches on a different instrument.

```scheme
;; Transpose and switch instrument (conceptual)
(define (transpose-revoice melody shift instrument)
  (let ((shifted (transpose melody shift)))
    (map (lambda (n)
           (part (voice instrument)
                 (list (list (car n) (caddr n)))))
         shifted)))

(transpose-revoice '((262 0.0 0.3) (330 0.3 0.3)) 1.5 'flute)
```
*[needs: transpose, voice, part]*

The melody, transposed up a fifth, is now voiced by a flute.

---

## Handling Non-Pitched Content

If the input is pure noise or a transient with no clear pitch, transcription may return an empty list or a marker.

```scheme
;; Transcribe white noise
(let ((n (noise 'white 0.5)))
  (transcribe n))
;; => ()  ; or ((nil 0.0 0.5))
```
*[needs: transcribe, noise]*

Transposition is undefined for unpitched material (or could shift the spectral centroid).

---

## Transposing by Harmonic Series Ratio

Use ratios from the harmonic series (2:1, 3:2, 4:3, 5:4) for pure intervals.

```scheme
(define harmonic-ratios
  '((octave . 2.0)
    (fifth . 1.5)
    (fourth . 1.333)
    (major-third . 1.25)
    (minor-third . 1.2)))

(let ((melody '((440 0.0 0.5)))
      (shift (cdr (assoc 'fifth harmonic-ratios))))
  (transpose melody shift))
;; => ((660 0.0 0.5))  ; just fifth
```
*[needs: transpose]*

---

## Transposing a Melody to a Target Range

Shift a melody so its lowest note matches a target, preserving intervals.

```scheme
(define (transpose-to-floor melody target-floor)
  (let* ((pitches (map car melody))
         (current-floor (apply min pitches))
         (ratio (/ target-floor current-floor)))
    (transpose melody ratio)))

(let ((mel '((262 0.0 0.3) (330 0.3 0.3) (392 0.6 0.3))))
  (transpose-to-floor mel 440))
;; => melody shifted so C4 (262) becomes A4 (440)
```
*[needs: transpose]*

---

## Transposing with a Pitch Curve

Vary the transposition ratio over time (conceptual).

<!-- BUILD: time-varying transpose or per-note ratio list -->

```scheme
;; Transpose each note by a different ratio (glissando effect)
(define (transpose-curve melody ratios)
  (map (lambda (note ratio)
         (list (* (car note) ratio)
               (cadr note)
               (caddr note)))
       melody ratios))

(transpose-curve '((262 0.0 0.3) (330 0.3 0.3) (392 0.6 0.3))
                 '(1.0 1.2 1.4))
;; => each note shifted by increasing ratio
```

---

## Auto-Tune by Snapping to Scale

Transcribe, then snap each detected pitch to the nearest scale degree, then play back.

<!-- BUILD: scale-snap function, requires scale definition -->

```scheme
;; Snap a pitch to the nearest semitone (12-TET quantize)
(define (snap-to-semitone pitch)
  (let* ((semitones-from-a4 (* 12 (/ (log (/ pitch 440)) (log 2))))
         (rounded (round semitones-from-a4)))
    (* 440 (expt 2 (/ rounded 12)))))

(snap-to-semitone 448)  ; close to A4
;; => 440.0
```

Apply to all transcribed notes:

```scheme
(define (auto-tune melody)
  (map (lambda (n)
         (list (snap-to-semitone (car n))
               (cadr n)
               (caddr n)))
       melody))

(auto-tune '((448 0.0 0.5) (335 0.5 0.5)))
;; => ((440 0.0 0.5) (329.63 0.5 0.5))  ; snapped
```

---

## Tempo-Scaled Transcription

If the original audio is at one tempo and we want to play it back at another, scale the start times and durations.

```scheme
(define (tempo-scale melody factor)
  (map (lambda (n)
         (list (car n)
               (* (cadr n) factor)
               (* (caddr n) factor)))
       melody))

(tempo-scale '((440 0.0 0.5) (494 0.5 0.5)) 0.5)
;; => ((440 0.0 0.25) (494 0.25 0.25))  ; double speed
```

---

## Transcribe-Transpose-Tempo: Full Transform

```scheme
(define (transform melody pitch-shift tempo-factor)
  (tempo-scale (transpose melody pitch-shift) tempo-factor))

(let ((mel '((262 0.0 0.5) (330 0.5 0.5))))
  (transform mel 1.5 0.5))
;; => up a fifth, double speed
```
*[needs: transpose]*

---

## Looping a Transcribed Phrase

Repeat the transcribed melody by appending copies with shifted start times.

```scheme
(define (loop-melody melody count)
  (let ((duration (apply max (map (lambda (n) (+ (cadr n) (caddr n)))
                                  melody))))
    (apply append
           (map (lambda (i)
                  (map (lambda (n)
                         (list (car n)
                               (+ (cadr n) (* i duration))
                               (caddr n)))
                       melody))
                (iota count)))))

(loop-melody '((262 0.0 0.3) (330 0.3 0.3)) 3)
;; => three repetitions, end-to-end
```

(Assumes `iota` available or define inline.)

```scheme
(define (iota n)
  (let loop ((i 0) (acc '()))
    (if (= i n) (reverse acc)
        (loop (+ i 1) (cons i acc)))))

(define (loop-melody melody count)
  (let ((duration (apply max (map (lambda (n) (+ (cadr n) (caddr n)))
                                  melody))))
    (apply append
           (map (lambda (i)
                  (map (lambda (n)
                         (list (car n)
                               (+ (cadr n) (* i duration))
                               (caddr n)))
                       melody))
                (iota count)))))

(loop-melody '((262 0.0 0.3) (330 0.3 0.3)) 2)
;; => ((262 0.0 0.3) (330 0.3 0.3) (262 0.6 0.3) (330 0.9 0.3))
```

---

## Transposing Each Loop Iteration

```scheme
(define (iota n)
  (let loop ((i 0) (acc '()))
    (if (= i n) (reverse acc)
        (loop (+ i 1) (cons i acc)))))

(define (loop-transpose melody count shift-per-loop)
  (apply append
         (map (lambda (i)
                (let ((ratio (expt shift-per-loop i)))
                  (transpose melody ratio)))
              (iota count))))

(loop-transpose '((262 0.0 0.3)) 3 1.5)
;; => C, G, D (each loop up a fifth)
```
*[needs: transpose]*

---

## Detecting and Transposing Octave Errors

If transcription misidentifies the octave, detect outliers and correct.

```scheme
(define (octave-correct melody)
  (let* ((pitches (map car melody))
         (median (list-ref (sort pitches <) (quotient (length pitches) 2))))
    (map (lambda (n)
           (let ((p (car n)))
             (cond ((> p (* median 2)) (list (/ p 2) (cadr n) (caddr n)))
                   ((< p (/ median 2)) (list (* p 2) (cadr n) (caddr n)))
                   (else n))))
         melody)))

(octave-correct '((262 0.0 0.3) (2640 0.3 0.3) (330 0.6 0.3)))
;; => ((262 0.0 0.3) (1320 0.3 0.3) (330 0.6 0.3))
```

(Assumes `sort` available or define.)

---

## Rendering Transcription to Staff Notation

Convert pitches to MIDI note numbers, then to staff positions. This is visualization, not synthesis.

[VISUAL: Transcribed pitches rendered as notes on a treble clef staff, with transposed version on a second staff below]

```scheme
(define (hz-to-midi pitch)
  (round (+ 69 (* 12 (/ (log (/ pitch 440)) (log 2))))))

(map hz-to-midi '(262 330 392 523))
;; => (60 64 67 72)  ; C4 E4 G4 C5
```

---

## Transposing MIDI Note Numbers

```scheme
(define (transpose-midi notes semitones)
  (map (lambda (n) (+ n semitones)) notes))

(transpose-midi '(60 64 67) 7)
;; => (67 71 74)  ; C → G, up a fifth
```

---

## Pitch-Class Transposition (Modulo Octave)

Transpose within the octave by taking modulo 12 after shift.

```scheme
(define (pitch-class note)
  (modulo note 12))

(map pitch-class '(60 64 67 72))
;; => (0 4 7 0)  ; C E G C
```

Transpose pitch-classes:

```scheme
(define (transpose-pc pc-list semitones)
  (map (lambda (pc) (modulo (+ pc semitones) 12)) pc-list))

(transpose-pc '(0 4 7) 7)
;; => (7 11 2)  ; C-E-G → G-B-D
```

---

## Full Example: Capture, Transcribe, Transpose, Play

```scheme
;; Record a phrase, transcribe it, transpose up a major third, play on a new voice
(define (capture-transpose-play-full)
  (let* ((original (list (tone 262 0.3)
                         (tone 294 0.3)
                         (tone 330 0.3)
                         (tone 349 0.3)))
         (notes (transcribe original))
         (shifted (transpose notes 1.2599)))  ; major third
    (map (lambda (n)
           (tone (car n) (caddr n)))
         shifted)))

(capture-transpose-play-full)
;; => C-D-E-F transposed to E-F#-G#-A#
```
*[needs: transcribe, transpose]*

---

## Chromatic vs. Diatonic Transposition

Chromatic transposition (what we've done) shifts by exact ratio, crossing scale boundaries. Diatonic transposition shifts by scale degrees, staying in key. For diatonic, we'd need a scale map.

<!-- BUILD: diatonic transpose requires scale-degree mapping -->

Chromatic example (already shown): multiply by 1.5 → fifth.

Diatonic (conceptual): given scale [C D E F G A B], shifting C by two degrees → E (a third in C major), not a fixed ratio but a lookup.

We focus on chromatic here; diatonic belongs in the Music book's harmony chapter.

---

## Exercise: Transcribe and Double

Write a program that takes a recording of a melody, transcribes it, duplicates it one octave lower, and plays both layers simultaneously.

---

## Exercise: Transpose by User Interval

Write a function `(user-transpose melody interval-name)` where `interval-name` is a symbol like `'perfect-fifth` or `'major-third`, using a lookup table you define.

---

## Exercise: Auto-Tune to Major Scale

Transcribe a slightly out-of-tune melody and snap each note to the nearest pitch in the C major scale (C D E F G A B C), then play it back in tune.

---

## Exercise: Transpose Chain

Write a program that takes a short melody and produces a chain of transpositions, each up a perfect fourth from the last, repeating five times. Play the result as a rising sequence.

---

## Exercise: Pitch Histogram

Transcribe a longer piece, extract all the pitches (ignoring timing), compute a histogram (count of each pitch-class modulo octave), and print the result. This reveals the pitch-class distribution.

---

## Exercise: Round-Trip with Tempo and Pitch Shift

Record a phrase, transcribe it, transpose it up a minor third, slow it down to half speed, and play it back. Then reverse the process: speed it back up, transpose down a minor third, and compare to the original.

---

**End of Chapter 14.** You can now hear sound, write down what you heard, shift it to a new key, and play it back on any instrument. The next chapter adds the human voice—formant vowels and word-level speech—where transcription meets language and Sound greets Speech.
